<p><a id=3D"Definition" name=3D"Definition"></a></p>
<h2>What is Meant by Interior Angles of a Polygon?</h2>
<p>An interior angle of a polygon is an angle formed inside the two adjacen=
t sides of a polygon. Or, we can say that the angle measures at the interio=
r part of a polygon are called the interior angle of a polygon. We know tha=
t the polygon can be classified into two different types, namely:</p>
<ul>
<li>Regular Polygon</li>
<li>Irregular Polygon</li>
</ul>
<p>For a regular polygon, all the interior angles are of the same measure. =
But for irregular polygon, each interior angle may have different measureme=
nts.</p>
<table class=3D"table table-bordered">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><strong><em>Also, read:</em></strong><p></p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://byjus.com/maths/exterior-angles-of-polygon/">Exterio=
r Angles of a Polygon</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://byjus.com/maths/alternate-interior-angles/">Alternat=
e Interior Angles</a></li>
</ul>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><a id=3D"Sum of interior angles" name=3D"Sum of interior angles"></a></p=
>
<h2>Sum of Interior Angles of a Polygon</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The Sum of interior angles of a polygo=
n is always a constant value. If the polygon is regular or irregular, the s=
um of its interior angles remains the same. Therefore, the sum of the inter=
ior angles of the polygon is given by the formula:</span></p>
<p><b>Sum of the Interior Angles of a Polygon =3D 180 (n-2) degrees</b></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">As we know, there are different types =
of polygons. Therefore, the number of interior angles and the respective su=
m of angles is given below in the table.</span></p>
<table class=3D"table-bordered">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><strong>Polygon Name</strong></td>
<td><strong>Number of Interior Angles</strong></td>
<td><strong>Sum of Interior Angles =3D (n-2) x 180=C2=B0</strong><span styl=
e=3D"font-weight: 400;">&nbsp;</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Triangle</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">3</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">180</span><b>=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Quadrilateral</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">4</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">360</span><b>=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Pentagon</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">5</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">540</span><b>=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Hexagon</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">6</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">720</span><b>=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Septagon</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">7</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">900</span><b>=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Octagon</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">8</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">1080</span><b>=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Nonagon</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">9</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">1260</span><b>=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Decagon</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">10</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">1440</span><b>=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><a id=3D"Interior angles of triangle" name=3D"Interior angles of triangl=
e"></a></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Interior angles of Triangles</span></=
h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A triangle is a polygon that has three=
 sides and three angles. Since, we know, there is a total of three </span><=
a href=3D"https://byjus.com/maths/triangles/"><span style=3D"font-weight: 4=
00;">types of triangles</span></a><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> based =
on sides and angles. But the angle of the sum of all the types of interior =
angles is always equal to 180 degrees. For a regular triangle, each interio=
r angle will be equal to:</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">180/3 =3D 60 degrees</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">60=C2=B0+60=C2=B0+60=C2=B0 =3D 180=C2=
=B0</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Therefore, no matter if the triangle i=
s an acute triangle or obtuse triangle or a right triangle, the sum of all =
its interior angles will always be 180 degrees.</span></p>
<p><a id=3D"Interior angles of quadrilateral" name=3D"Interior angles of qu=
adrilateral"></a></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Interior Angles of Quadrilaterals</sp=
an></h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">In geometry, we have come across diffe=
rent types of quadrilaterals, such as:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Square</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Rectangle</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Parallelogram</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Rhombus</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Trapezium</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Kite</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">All the shapes listed above have four =
sides and four angles. The common property for all the above four-sided sha=
pes is the sum of interior angles is always equal to 360 degrees. For a reg=
ular quadrilateral such as square, each interior angle will be equal to:</s=
pan></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">360/4 =3D 90 degrees.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">90=C2=B0 + 90=C2=B0 + 90=C2=B0 + 90=C2=
=B0 =3D 360=C2=B0</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Since each quadrilateral is made up of=
 two triangles, therefore the sum of interior angles of two triangles is eq=
ual to 360 degrees and hence for the quadrilateral.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><a id=3D"Interior angles of pentagon" name=3D"Interior angles of pentago=
n"></a></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Interior angles of Pentagon</span></h=
3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">In case of the pentagon, it has five s=
ides and also it can be formed by joining three triangles side by side. Thu=
s, if one triangle has sum of angles equal to 180 degrees, therefore, the s=
um of angles of three triangles will be:</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">3 x 180 =3D 540 degrees</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Thus, the angle sum of the pentagon is=
 540 degrees.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">For a regular pentagon, each angle wil=
l be equal to:</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">540=C2=B0/5 =3D 108=C2=B0</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">108=C2=B0+108=C2=B0+108=C2=B0+108=C2=
=B0+108=C2=B0 =3D 540=C2=B0</span></p>
<table>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>Sum of Interior angles of a Polygon =3D (Number of triangles formed =
in the polygon) x 180=C2=B0</b></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><a id=3D"Interior angles of regular polygon" name=3D"Interior angles of =
regular polygon"></a></p>
<h2>Interior angles of Regular Polygons</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A regular polygon has all its angles e=
qual in measure.</span></p>
<table class=3D"table-bordered">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Regular Polygon Name</span></td>
