<p><a id=3D"Formulas" name=3D"Formulas"></a></p>
<h2>Interior Angle Formulas</h2>
<p>The interior angles of a polygon always lie inside the polygon. The form=
ula can be obtained in three ways. Let us discuss the three different formu=
las in detail.</p>
<p><strong>Method 1:</strong></p>
<p>If =E2=80=9Cn=E2=80=9D is the number of sides of a polygon, then the for=
mula is given below:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Interior angles of a Regular Polyg=
on =3D [180=C2=B0(n) =E2=80=93 360=C2=B0] / n</strong></p>
<p><strong>Method 2:</strong></p>
<p>If the exterior angle of a polygon is given, then the formula to find th=
e interior angle is</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Interior Angle of a polygon =3D 18=
0=C2=B0 =E2=80=93 Exterior angle of a polygon</strong></p>
<p><strong>Method 3:</strong></p>
<p>If we know the sum of all the interior angles of a regular polygon, we c=
an obtain the interior angle by dividing the sum by the number of sides.</p=
>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Interior Angle =3D Sum of the inte=
rior angles of a polygon / n</strong></p>
<p>Where</p>
<p>=E2=80=9Cn=E2=80=9D is the number of polygon sides.</p>
<p><a id=3D"Interior angle theorem" name=3D"Interior angle theorem"></a></p=
>
<h2>Interior Angles Theorem</h2>
<p>Below is the proof for the polygon interior angle sum theorem</p>
<p><strong>Statement:</strong></p>
<p>In a polygon of =E2=80=98n=E2=80=99 sides, the sum of the interior angle=
s is equal to (2n =E2=80=93 4) =C3=97 90=C2=B0.</p>
<p><strong>To prove:</strong></p>
<p>The sum of the interior angles =3D (2n =E2=80=93 4) right angles</p>
<p><strong>Proof:</strong></p>
<p><img class=3D"alignnone" src=3D"https://cdn1.byjus.com/wp-content/upload=
s/2021/04/Interior-Angles-of-a-Polygon.png" alt=3D"Interior angles example"=
 width=3D"750" height=3D"350"></p>
<p>ABCDE is a =E2=80=9Cn=E2=80=9D sided polygon. Take any point O inside th=
e polygon. Join OA, OB, OC.</p>
<p>For =E2=80=9Cn=E2=80=9D sided polygon, the polygon forms =E2=80=9Cn=E2=
=80=9D triangles.</p>
<p>We know that the sum of the angles of a triangle is equal to 180 degrees=
</p>
<p>Therefore, the sum of the angles of n triangles =3D n =C3=97 180=C2=B0</=
p>
<p>From the above statement, we can say that</p>
<p>Sum of interior angles + Sum of the angles at O =3D 2n =C3=97 90=C2=B0 =
=E2=80=94=E2=80=94(1)</p>
<p>But, the sum of the angles at O =3D 360=C2=B0</p>
<p>Substitute the above value in (1), we get</p>
<p>Sum of interior angles + 360=C2=B0=3D 2n =C3=97 90=C2=B0</p>
<p>So, the sum of the interior angles =3D (2n =C3=97 90=C2=B0) =E2=80=93 36=
0=C2=B0</p>
<p>Take 90 as common, then it becomes</p>
<p>The sum of the interior angles =3D (2n =E2=80=93 4) =C3=97 90=C2=B0</p>
<p>Therefore, the sum of =E2=80=9Cn=E2=80=9D interior angles is (2n =E2=80=
=93 4) =C3=97 90=C2=B0</p>
<p><strong>So, each interior angle of a regular polygon is [(2n =E2=80=93 4=
) =C3=97 90=C2=B0] / n</strong></p>
<p><strong><em>Note: </em></strong>In a regular polygon, all the interior a=
ngles are of the same measure.<br>
<a id=3D"Exterior angles of Polygon" name=3D"Exterior angles of Polygon"></=
a></p>
<h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Exterior Angles&nbsp;</span></h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Exterior angles of a polygon are the a=
ngles at the vertices of the polygon, that lie outside the shape. The angle=
s are formed by one side of the polygon and extension of the other side. Th=
e sum of an adjacent interior angle and exterior angle for any polygon is e=
qual to 180 degrees since they form a linear pair. Also, the sum of exterio=
r angles of a polygon is always equal to 360 degrees.</span></p>
